{
  "texts": [
    "Among the intra-parameter methods, LoRA is the most widely used one, because it can achieve a comparable or better downstream adaptation performance to the full fine-tuning on a range of downstream tasks [9] and is easy to implement.",
    "Besides, there are many variants have been proposed to further improve the downstream adaptation ability of LoRA on more challenging downstream tasks.LoRA achieves parameter efficiency by updating the dense neural network layers of an LLM with pluggable low-rank matrices.",
    "These matrices (a.k.a, LoRA plugins) are independent of the LLM, which can be stored and reused in other related downstream tasks.",
    "Furthermore, these LoRA plugins can be combined to achieve cross-task generalization, which can facilitate multi-task learning, domain adaptation, and continual learning.As the LoRA modules accumulate, the computation cost of managing LoRA modules is increasing.",
    "Although LoRA is computation-efficient, the computational cost of managing a larger number of LoRA modules is unignorable."
  ]
}